     1	# Curbside Commons
     2	
     3	**An independent, deterministic verifier for agentic commerce: it checks what delivery platforms and AI-agent surfaces *say* about a merchant against the merchant's own system of record, and audits fee statements against codified law.**
     4	
     5	A **human-led, AI-assisted** prototype, built and reviewed under a dual-model engineering process. The load-bearing claims in this file are backed by committed tests or records in this repo, each stated with its measure and date ‚Äî declared claims, individually evidenced; this is not a blanket claim that every sentence of prose has machine coverage.
     6	
     7	> **Not affiliated with, endorsed by, or connected to** DoorDash, Uber Eats, Grubhub, Square, Toast, OpenAI, Stripe, Google, or any named business or protocol body. This is an independent, company-agnostic prototype. **The truth-audit engine runs entirely on a labeled synthetic corpus** ‚Äî no real merchant relationship, account, data, or PII anywhere, and no real business-impact claims. All metrics are simulated or measured on synthetic fixtures, and every artifact says so on its face. (The archived legacy module's data provenance is scoped separately ‚Äî see [Lineage](#lineage).)
     8	
     9	## Try it in 60 seconds
    10	
    11	```bash
    12	npm install
    13	node bin/check.mjs demo                                          # the scripted walkthrough, $0, zero-config
    14	node bin/check.mjs check <feed.json> --against <catalog.json>    # truth leg (exit 1 = drift found)
    15	node bin/check.mjs check <doc.json> --conformance                # conformance leg (pinned UCP schemas)
    16	node bin/check.mjs fees <statement.json>                         # NYC ¬ß20-563.3 fee audit
    17	npm run verify                                                   # typecheck + lint + tests + build
    18	```
    19	
    20	The demo plays one scripted scene: "a spec-faithful simulated agent follows a spec-valid but false surface; the verifier catches the surface/SOR mismatch." Every verdict in the transcript is computed by the real verifier, never narrated ‚Äî labeled *spec-faithful demonstration actor ‚Äî simulated* throughout.
    21	
    22	Zero network and zero LLM calls on every CLI path ‚Äî enforced structurally by an import-graph eval, not by promise. A desktop web console (`npm run dev`: `/report`, `/demo`) renders the same machine reports in two registers, plain words first.
    23	
    24	## The evals harness is the product's character
    25	
    26	Everything asserted here is measured under committed, tamper-locked evaluation:
    27	
    28	- **Pre-registered floors, in git, before any live run.** The LLM classifier's pass bars were committed before its exam; floors only ever tighten pre-run and never move after results. The first run (2026-07-05) scored 20/21 and missed one per-class recall floor ‚Äî so its label honestly read **DEFERRED**, and that record stands unedited. Earning the label took a second owner-authorized exam on a **fresh pre-registered held-out split** (the first split was exposed and never re-scored): **21/21, every floor cleared (2026-07-09)**. The bar never moved in either run.
    29	- **Eval-locks.** Every live run's raw results are frozen into the repo, and committed lock tests recompute the headline numbers from the per-item records forever ‚Äî the grade cannot be quietly edited, and "just run it again" cannot replace what happened.
    30	- **Anti-theater baselines.** An LLM component must beat a pinned deterministic baseline on held-out gold before its label counts; ties lose.
    31	- **Structural $0 enforcement.** Import-graph evals prove the CLI, demo, delivery builders, and web views cannot reach an LLM or the network ‚Äî not a promise, a failing test.
    32	- **Frozen corpus and goldens.** Fixtures are seeded and freeze-locked (regenerate ‚áí bytes must match); reports byte-compare against goldens.
    33	
    34	## The problem, in plain words
    35	
    36	When you order food through an app, or tell an AI assistant to do it, the menu being acted on is **not the restaurant's actual menu**. It is a copy, passed along a chain: the merchant's till system ‚Üí sync software ‚Üí marketplaces ‚Üí and now AI agents. Copies go stale: the price went up and the copy didn't, the wings sold out an hour ago, a fee got renamed on a payout statement.
    37	
    38	A human shrugs at a stale menu. **An AI agent doesn't shrug ‚Äî it places the order.** And every seat in that chain has a conflict of interest: platforms won't audit each other, sync vendors would be grading their own homework, and it isn't the AI companies' job. A credible referee has to sit outside all of those incentives ‚Äî verifying claims against the merchant's own system of record rather than against another copy. That mechanism, applied with measurement rigor, is what this prototype demonstrates (others work on adjacent trust problems; the differentiation claimed here is the mechanism and the discipline, not exclusivity).
    39	
    40	1. **Truth leg** ‚Äî compare a serving copy (an ACP-style feed, or a UCP catalog response) line by line against the merchant's system of record. Deterministic. No LLM anywhere on this path.
    41	2. **Conformance leg** ‚Äî validate a UCP catalog response against the **78 pinned official UCP JSON Schemas** (spec `v2026-04-08`). A document can be perfectly spec-shaped and still false, which is the point:
    42	
    43	> **The headline exhibit, machine-checked in CI:** `fixtures/ucp-conformance-ci/valid/conformant-but-false.json` **passes** official-schema conformance and **fails** the truth leg on a price lie. Shape-valid is not true.
    44	
    45	3. **Fee-audit leg** ‚Äî audit a monthly delivery fee statement against the codified **NYC ¬ß 20-563.3** fee caps (17-rule table built from primary legal text, 11 statement-checkable rules implemented, 6 registered as not statement-checkable with written reasons). Deterministic, $0.
    46	4. **Demo** ‚Äî the scripted walkthrough above. Scripted, deterministic, labeled *spec-faithful demonstration actor ‚Äî simulated*; every verdict computed by the real verifier.
    47	
