    16	
    17	## The problem, in plain words
    18	
    19	When you order food through an app ‚Äî or, starting now, when you just tell an AI assistant "order me a pizza" ‚Äî the menu you see is **not the restaurant's actual menu**. It's a **copy**. The real menu lives in the restaurant's till system (their cash-register software). That copy gets passed along a chain: till ‚Üí sync software ‚Üí DoorDash / Uber Eats / Grubhub ‚Üí and now ‚Üí AI assistants like ChatGPT, Claude, and Gemini.
    20	
    21	Copies go stale:
    22	
    23	- The restaurant raised the pizza to $18.99 ‚Äî the app still says $16.99.
    24	- They ran out of wings an hour ago ‚Äî the app still shows them as available.
    25	- A fee got renamed on the payout statement ‚Äî nobody can tell what it actually is anymore.
    26	
    27	A **human** shrugs at this. You see something off, you close the app. Minor annoyance.
    28	
    29	An **AI assistant doesn't shrug ‚Äî it just places the order.** Wrong price ‚Üí the restaurant eats the difference. Sold-out item ‚Üí cancelled order, refund, an "error charge" the restaurant pays for. And this is not a future problem: since **mid-2026** the major consumer AI assistants can order food for real, and assistant-based delivery ordering has been piloting since March 2026. (The named companies and dates are in the repo's research digests ‚Äî this explainer keeps the prose generic on purpose.)
    30	
    31	Here's the trap that keeps this problem alive: **everyone who could fix it has a conflict of interest.**
    32	
    33	- The delivery apps won't audit each other.
    34	- The menu-sync companies won't audit their own syncing ‚Äî that's grading your own homework.
    35	- The AI companies won't audit restaurant data ‚Äî not their job.
    36	
    37	So none of them is positioned to be the neutral checker of whether what the apps and AI assistants *say* about a restaurant matches what's *actually true* in the restaurant's own system. A **neutral referee** has to sit outside those conflicts ‚Äî checking the copies against the restaurant's own records. That referee role is what this project demonstrates. (Others work on nearby trust problems; what's demonstrated here is the specific mechanism ‚Äî checking against the source of truth ‚Äî done with published measurements, not a claim that no one else is trying.)
    38	
    39	## The use case, in one question
    40	
    41	A restaurant owner (or a platform, or a sync vendor) asks:
    42	
    43	> **"Is what the apps and AI agents are showing about my restaurant actually true right now?"**
    44	
    45	Right prices. Right items. Right availability. And later (module two): **are the fees taken out of my payouts actually what my contract and the law say?** Answering either question today means checking by hand, line by line. The one time regulators did check fees by hand (New York City, April 2026), they found a delivery app had overcharged 380+ restaurants and made it pay $875,000 back.
    46	
    47	## The solution: build the referee
    48	
    49	An independent checker that compares the copies against the truth. In plain steps:
    50	
    51	1. **Take the truth** ‚Äî the restaurant's own till/catalog data (with their permission).
    52	2. **Take the copies** ‚Äî what the delivery apps and AI-assistant feeds are showing.
    53	3. **Compare, line by line.** Price vs price, item vs item, available vs available. Boring, exact, mechanical ‚Äî like a spellchecker for menus. No AI needed for this part, so it can't hallucinate.
    54	4. **Where it's genuinely fuzzy, AI judges carefully.** Is "Lg Pepp Pizza" the same item as "Large Pepperoni Pizza"? That's the only place AI is used ‚Äî and we measure how accurate the AI judge is, and publish the measurement.
    55	5. **Report with receipts.** Every mismatch shown with evidence: *here's your system saying $18.99, here's the app saying $16.99, since Tuesday.*
    56	6. **A human approves any fix.** The tool never changes anything on its own. It recommends; a person decides.
    57	
    58	**How it ships:** as open tooling anyone in the industry can pick up and run ‚Äî a checker for the newly published AI-ordering data formats. Those standards are young, and they standardize the *shape* of the data, not its *truth*. What this project puts on the table is the independent truth-check itself ‚Äî against the restaurant's own records, with its accuracy measured and published ‚Äî rather than a claim to be the first or only one trying.
    59	
    60	**The demo that makes it click:** we set up a fake restaurant, deliberately break its menu copy (a wrong price on an item), and let a **rule-following stand-in shopping agent** read the broken copy ‚Äî the same published feed any AI assistant would read, and nothing else (it never sees the restaurant's records). Following the format exactly, it picks the item and is ready to order at the price the copy shows. **The verifier then checks that same copy against the restaurant's records and catches the difference the agent had no way to see** ‚Äî the served price versus the true price, with receipts. The demo stops right there, at the moment of selection (no pretend checkout). It closes with the sharpest exhibit: the same kind of menu answer can **pass the official format rulebook and still quote a wrong price** ‚Äî correctly shaped is not the same as true. You don't need to understand any of the technology to follow it. (Simulated throughout; $0; no AI runs in the demo ‚Äî it is exact, repeatable logic.)
    61	
    62	## One-sentence version
    63	
    64	> **AI assistants are starting to order food from copies of restaurant menus that are often wrong ‚Äî we're building the neutral fact-checker that catches the lies before the AI acts on them.**
    65	
    66	## What we are NOT claiming (honesty box)
    67	
    68	- This is a **prototype run on demand for demonstrations** ‚Äî not a live 24/7 service.
    69	- Demo restaurants and their data are **synthetic (made up) and clearly labeled**; the *rules* we check against (published data-format standards, real fee laws) are real and cited.
    70	- No real DoorDash/Uber Eats/Grubhub merchant accounts, data, or business impact are involved or implied.
    71	- AI is used in **one narrow, measured spot** (fuzzy matching / judging), with humans approving anything that acts. The comparing itself is deterministic ‚Äî exact, repeatable arithmetic.
    72	- Built human-led, AI-assisted, professionally reviewed.
