     1	# The writeup ‚Äî a truth layer for agentic commerce
     2	
     3	*Publication draft (Pub slice, plan ¬ß5). Written 2026-07-06; refreshed 2026-07-10 to the records earned since (classifier calibration, live agent floors, the recorded send, the public deploy). Dated claims are source-backed in `docs/research/` (source lockfile included); market-event prose is genericized by policy, with the named, dated citations preserved in the research digests. This document is the postable narrative; the repo README is the technical front door. Human-led, AI-assisted, professionally reviewed.*
     4	
     5	---
     6	
     7	## The one-sentence pitch
     8	
     9	AI agents started ordering food this year, acting on data that can be perfectly spec-shaped and still false. So we built an independent referee for it: an open, deterministic verifier that compares what platforms and agent surfaces *say* about a merchant with the merchant's own records, and audits fee statements against codified law ‚Äî with its own accuracy measured and published.
    10	
    11	## Why this, why now
    12	
    13	Three dated facts frame the moment (each source-backed in the repo's research digests):
    14	
    15	1. **Agentic ordering is live.** Since mid-2026 the major consumer AI assistants can place real food orders through published commerce protocols, and marketplace ordering inside an assistant has been piloting since March 2026 (named, dated citations in the research digests). An agent doesn't eyeball a menu and shrug at a stale price ‚Äî it acts on it.
    16	2. **The protocol layer standardizes *shape*, not *truth*.** ACP and UCP (with its Food vertical) are settling fast as the rails of agentic commerce ‚Äî and a document can satisfy either spec perfectly while being false about the merchant it describes.
    17	3. **Fee enforcement got real.** New York City's first restaurant-side fee-cap enforcement was an $875,000+ settlement, including over $580,000 in restitution to 380+ restaurants (announced 2026-04-08); the violations were found by hand, and DCWP now has an active rulemaking on recordkeeping for fee-cap compliance (hearing July 2026). The law is asking for exactly the kind of audit this repo automates on synthetic statements.
    18	
    19	Every seat that could verify the copies is conflicted: platforms won't audit each other, sync vendors would grade their own homework, agent vendors say not-our-job. A credible referee has to sit outside all three incentive sets and verify against the merchant's own system of record. This prototype demonstrates that seat ‚Äî the mechanism and the measurement rigor, not a claim of exclusivity (adjacent trust tooling exists; checking against the structured source of truth, with published calibration, is the differentiation).
    20	
    21	## What the verifier shows
    22	
    23	**The headline, machine-checked in the committed test suite:** a catalog response can pass the official UCP schema validation and still lie about the price. The exhibit file (`fixtures/ucp-conformance-ci/valid/conformant-but-false.json`) passes conformance and fails the truth leg in the same test run. Spec-valid is not true ‚Äî which is precisely why a conformance checker alone can't hold the referee seat.
    24	
    25	**The demo, in one line (verbatim, single-sourced in code):** "a spec-faithful simulated agent follows a spec-valid but false surface; the verifier catches the surface/SOR mismatch." Run `node bin/check.mjs demo` ‚Äî deterministic, $0, zero-config; every verdict in the transcript is computed by the real verifier.
    26	
    27	**The fee-audit leg:** NYC ¬ß 20-563.3's caps, codified from primary legal text into a 17-rule table (11 statement-checkable rules implemented; 6 honestly registered as not checkable from a statement, with written reasons), applied to simulated monthly statements with receipts on every finding: claim, reference row, rule id, severity. An eval asserts no finding exists without all four.
    28	
    29	## The part we're proudest of: a measurement that says no
    30	
    31	Inside the fee-audit lane, an LLM serves as an advisory line-item classifier for fuzzy fee-relabeling cases. Before its label could count, it had to clear pre-registered floors on a held-out split; the floors were committed to git *before* the run, with a no-rerun rule (a split is exposed once scored).
    32	
    33	**First run (2026-07-05):** it scored **20/21 accuracy, strictly beating the pinned deterministic baseline (19/21)**, with macro precision 0.971 and zero flip-rate across repetitions ‚Äî and its label read **DEFERRED**, because one per-class recall came in 0.75 against a pre-registered ‚â• 0.80 floor. We published the miss. The bar did not move.
    34	
    35	**Second run (2026-07-09, owner-armed):** a brand-new pre-registered held-out split (the exposed first split was never re-scored), floors identical to the first registration, committed before arming. Result: **21/21, every floor cleared** ‚Äî the label is now earned: *calibrated (fresh held-out, pre-registered floors, one pass)*. The 2026-07-05 DEFER stands unedited as history, and both runs' raw records are frozen by committed lock tests.
    36	
    37	In a field where "our AI is calibrated" is usually an adjective, this repo treats it as a conjunctive, pre-registered, machine-checked claim ‚Äî and earning it took a second exam on new questions under the same bars, not a re-grade. The measurement discipline is the product as much as the verifier is. (The same regime later extended to the agent lane: the two model-directed crew roles cleared pre-registered live-run floors 20/20 on 2026-07-07, so ‚Äî and only so ‚Äî they carry the "agent" label.)
    38	
    39	## What's real and what isn't (the honesty box)
    40	
    41	- **Synthetic corpus, labeled on every surface.** No real merchant data, accounts, or platform access anywhere; no real business-impact claims. The generators are seeded and the committed fixtures are freeze-locked (regenerate ‚áí bytes must match).
    42	- **A prototype run on demand, not an operated service.** The enterprise expansion path is documented, not built.
    43	- **Real law, real schemas.** The NYC rule table is codified from primary text; the 78 UCP JSON Schemas are pinned verbatim from the official spec repo (Apache-2.0, sha256-locked provenance) at `v2026-04-08`, still the current release as of 2026-07-06.
    44	- **Open questions stay open.** Fee verdicts depending on the statutory "purchase price" base are type-enforced provisional; operator demand is unvalidated; real-world entity matching is harder than the synthetic-controlled matching demonstrated.
    45	
    46	## Numbers at a glance
    47	
    48	1001 tests passing (+7 skipped live harnesses; re-measured live 2026-07-10) ¬∑ 8/8 listings drift classes injected and caught (measured) ¬∑ 33/35 agreement with the official Rust validator with the 2 divergences documented to their root cause (the JSON Schema 2020-12 format-assertion fork) ¬∑ 17 fee rules codified, 11 implemented + 6 registered non-checkable ¬∑ classifier **calibrated 2026-07-09**: 21/21 on a fresh pre-registered held-out split (first run 20/21 vs the 19/21 baseline, honestly deferred ‚Äî record stands) ¬∑ crew live run 20/20, Intake + Reviewer labeled agents ¬∑ one recorded owner-armed Slack send (2026-07-09), everything else structurally unable to send ¬∑ $0 of LLM spend on every CLI path, enforced by an import-graph eval.
