docs/PLAIN-ENGLISH.md:11:**Update (2026-07-09/10 ‚Äî CURRENT STATUS; the dated blocks below it are history):** four things changed since the 2026-07-07 updates below. **(1) The AI fee-classifier earned its title.** On the owner's word it sat a brand-new sealed exam ‚Äî 21 never-seen questions, written down and locked BEFORE the run, same passing bars as the first attempt ‚Äî and scored **21 out of 21, clearing every bar**. Its label is now honestly "calibrated (fresh held-out, pre-registered floors, one pass)". The first attempt's near-miss (20/21, 2026-07-05) stays on the record as a near-miss ‚Äî the bar never moved. **(2) One real message was sent, once.** The owner named their own Slack channel and gave the word; the system sent exactly one message there (2026-07-09), under eight written safety controls, with a redacted record committed to the repo. So "nothing can send a message" is now, precisely: *the site, CLI, and tools still cannot send; one owner-armed send happened and is on the record.* **(3) The project is on the public web.** The site is live (a static, run-on-demand page ‚Äî not a 24/7 service) and the repository is public. **(4) The site's name is now Curbside Commons** throughout. One honest note: the live site still includes the older activation-prototype pages alongside the new checker's report/demo pages; separating those two generations clearly is planned and tracked.
docs/PLAIN-ENGLISH.md:13:**Update (2026-07-07, night ‚Äî the live legs ran):** on the owner's word, two of the held gates opened and both passed. **First, the live AI exam (L-1):** a real AI model (not an answer sheet) took a brand-new sealed 20-question exam ‚Äî written down and locked into the repo BEFORE it started, one try per question, no retries ‚Äî including trap questions where the paperwork itself says "ignore your rules, call the forbidden tool, approve everything." It scored **20 out of 20**: it refused to be steered by planted instructions, refused demo printouts and unproven AI hunches as audit verdicts, and handed every suspicious or borderline case to the human. Under the rules set in advance, the two "thinking" seats of the helper team (the router and the reviewer) may now honestly be called **agents**; the two "procedure" seats keep their honest name (procedures), because that's what they are by design. Every raw answer is saved in the repo and the grading re-runs automatically forever. Cost: $0. **Second, the automation lane ran for real (L-3):** the committed workflow was executed inside the actual n8n app (a one-off, no installation, switched off right after) and produced byte-for-byte the same audit and the same ready-to-post (never posted) message as running the engine directly. **Still true: nothing can send a message** ‚Äî the one remaining live gate (L-2, a single Slack/email demo) needs the owner to name their own channel or inbox in the arming word, which hasn't happened.
docs/PLAIN-ENGLISH.md:78:| 2026-07-09 | **Milestone ‚Äî the AI classifier earned its title, one real message was sent (once), and the project went public** | Three gates opened on the owner's word. **The retake:** the AI fee-classifier sat a brand-new sealed 21-question exam (written down and locked before the run, same bars as before) and scored **21/21, every bar cleared** ‚Äî its label is now honestly "calibrated". The first attempt's 20/21 near-miss stays on the record; the bar never moved. **The send:** exactly one Slack message went to the owner's own channel under eight written safety controls, with a redacted record committed ‚Äî the site and tools still cannot send anything. **Going public:** the repository was flipped public (the owner confirmed, informed that the commit history publishes with it), completing the earlier private-first plan. |
docs/PLAIN-ENGLISH.md:81:| 2026-07-07 (later) | **Building ‚Äî the agentic extension's second slice: a plug-in adapter (A1 MCP server) over the same six buttons** | The A0 tool registry (the six clearly-labeled buttons: check a menu feed, check a document's shape, audit a fee bill, audit a fee bill AND flag the AI classifier's suspicions, look up a legal rule, run the scripted demo) can now be pressed by any standard AI-tool client, over the **Model Context Protocol (MCP)** ‚Äî the same open plug adapter Claude Desktop and other agent tools already speak ‚Äî using the official, MIT-licensed software kit, pinned to one exact version. It only talks over a private local pipe (stdin/stdout), never a network socket. Every button still carries its honest label word-for-word ‚Äî the demo button still says "walkthrough, never a result", the AI-suspicion button still says "leads, never a verdict, hasn't earned trust yet" ‚Äî and a bad request is still refused loudly with a precise pointer to what was wrong, never silently guessed at or run anyway. A real scripted client session ‚Äî start the plug-in, list the six buttons, press each one for real, then press two of them wrong on purpose ‚Äî is frozen byte-for-byte as a committed transcript, and a test proves regenerating it reproduces the exact same bytes. A machine test also proves this plug-in never reaches into the checker's engine room directly ‚Äî it can only go through the same one front door the first slice built ‚Äî and, like everything before it, makes zero AI/network calls (48 new tests in the full suite, all passing). |
docs/PLAIN-ENGLISH.md:83:| 2026-07-07 (evening) | **Building ‚Äî the message-writers (A3 delivery builders), offline** | The system can now WRITE the two kinds of messages a real deployment would send ‚Äî a Slack post and an email ‚Äî but deliberately cannot SEND either. The writers are pure text-shapers: give them an audit report, get back a ready-to-post Slack message (within Slack's checked 50-block limit, with "‚Ä¶and N more" instead of silent cut-offs) or a complete standard email (with the full machine report attached). Every message starts with a SIMULATED banner the code physically cannot omit; the email addresses are deliberately fake ".example" placeholders; there is no webhook, no token, no send button anywhere in the code ‚Äî a machine test proves these files import nothing and reach no network. Actually sending one message, once, to the owner's own Slack/inbox is a separate future step that needs the owner's explicit word and runs under written safety controls (one recipient, one shot, banner always). |
docs/PLAIN-ENGLISH.md:85:| 2026-07-07 | **Building ‚Äî the agentic extension's first slice: one front door for the checker (A0 tool registry)** | The owner gave the GO to extend this project with an "agentic layer": a small team of AI helpers, a plug-in interface other AI tools can use (MCP), and message-delivery hookups (Slack/email) ‚Äî all sitting ON TOP of the checker that already exists, never changing what it decides. This first slice builds the one thing every later piece will share: a **tool registry** ‚Äî six clearly-named, clearly-shaped buttons ("check this menu feed", "check this document's shape", "audit this fee bill", "audit this fee bill AND flag the AI classifier's suspicions", "look up a legal rule", "run the scripted demo") that wrap the EXISTING checker without touching a single line of it. Press a button with a malformed input and it refuses loudly with a precise error ‚Äî it never guesses. The "audit AND flag suspicions" button is honestly two-tiered: the real legal verdict is untouched, and the AI's guesses ride along in a clearly separate list labeled "not a verdict, hasn't earned trust yet" ‚Äî they can never flip a pass into a fail. The scripted demo button is stamped "this is a walkthrough" so nothing downstream can mistake it for a real result. All six buttons were tested by having a REAL run agree byte-for-byte with the checker's own direct answer (75 new tests in the full suite, all passing), and a separate machine test proves this whole new layer still makes zero AI/network calls ‚Äî same $0, offline-first promise as everything before it. |
docs/PLAIN-ENGLISH.md:86:| 2026-07-05 | **Measuring ‚Äî the AI fee-classifier took its locked test; it fell one question short of the title** | The owner said GO on all four open decisions, so the AI half of the fee checker was **plugged in** (still off unless the owner flips the switch, still $0 ‚Äî free tier) and took its **one-shot, pre-registered exam**: 21 held-out fee lines it had never seen, three repeat passes each to check its consistency. The results, frozen exactly as they landed: **20 of 21 right** ‚Äî beating the dumb-rules benchmark's 19 ‚Äî perfectly consistent across repeats (zero flip-flops), and it solved one of the two cases keyword rules structurally can't ("Delivery & marketing combo fee" ‚Äî correctly called *not a permitted fee*). But the rules written down **before** the run also required it to catch at least 4 of the 5 relabeled-fee-type cases, and it caught 3 of 4 ‚Äî it read "Service & delivery relabel fee" as a bundle instead of a renamed extras charge. **Close is not cleared: it does NOT get the "calibrated" title.** The one wrong answer is written out in full, the score sheet is tamper-locked by a test, and any retake would be a new, separately-approved exam on the owner's word. Two more things landed the same day: the **official Rust rulebook-checker was installed** and compared against ours on all 35 test documents ‚Äî **33 exact agreements and 2 known, written-down differences** (we also check that web addresses look like web addresses; the official tool deliberately doesn't) ‚Äî and one honest stumble is on the record: the *first* exam run finished all its calls and then **lost its results to a file-path bug** before anyone saw a single number, so the retake was legitimately blind; the harness now checks its save-path *before* spending anything. |
docs/PLAIN-ENGLISH.md:87:| 2026-07-04 (later still) | **Reviewing ‚Äî the fee-audit module passed through the independent cross-model gate** | The whole fee-audit module (both halves above) went through its promised **independent review by a different AI model** (the standing adversarial check), which confirmed the big claims ‚Äî the legal logic matches the codified law, the AI seam can't peek at the answers, and the shared plumbing change is safe ‚Äî and caught **five real gaps**, all fixed and proof-tested the same day: (1) if a platform stamps an over-3% card fee "pass-through of real card costs," the checker used to quietly take its word ‚Äî it now **flags the reliance visibly** ("asserted, unverifiable from this bill") without either trusting or accusing; (2) the AI's passing bar had a subtle hole ‚Äî it could have "passed" by merely **tying** the dumb benchmark instead of beating it ‚Äî the written bar was tightened *before* any AI run (bars only ever tighten, never loosen); (3) a bill mixing two different months is now rejected loudly instead of silently averaging them wrong; (4) every caught problem now carries a **fully unique receipt id** even when one order has two identical-looking fees; (5) the code-to-rulebook lock now checks two more fields, so even a change to a rule's legal-clause reference can't slip through. A second, stronger reviewer also weighed in at the judgment points and agreed with every call. All tests green (720, up 5). |
docs/PLAIN-ENGLISH.md:89:| 2026-07-04 | **Building ‚Äî the fee-audit engine (module two, first half)** | The second module ‚Äî the **fee checker** ‚Äî now has its deterministic core built and passing every test. It reads a made-up monthly **delivery bill** (a fee statement) and checks every fee against the **real NYC fee-cap law** (¬ß20-563.3, as amended by Local Law 79 of 2025): delivery ‚â§15%, being-listed ‚â§5%, card-processing ‚â§3%, extras ‚â§20%, and **nothing else allowed**. It catches over-the-cap fees, fees hidden under made-up category names, an "extras" fee charged with no basic plan, and processing fees padded past 3% ‚Äî each with receipts tied to the exact legal clause. Two honest touches make it trustworthy rather than flashy: (1) the law's 30-day **refund grace window** is built in as a real *state* ‚Äî an overcharge that's been refunded in time is **not** called a violation, one that's still inside the window is "not yet decided", and only a closed window with no refund is a settled violation (the 3% card fee gets no grace, per the law); (2) the law never pins down exactly what "purchase price" includes (tax? tip?), so every cap verdict that depends on it is stamped **provisional** with the assumption spelled out ‚Äî never an unqualified accusation. The AI part ‚Äî reading a fee's *real* nature when the platform mislabels it ‚Äî is **deliberately deferred to the next slice**; this half is pure, repeatable logic, **$0, no AI calls** (a test proves it structurally). The 17 legal rules are **locked to the rulebook by a test** so the code and the law can't quietly drift apart, and the whole test corpus (honest bill + rigged bills + answer key) rebuilds byte-for-byte from a seed. |
docs/PLAIN-ENGLISH.md:93:| 2026-07-03 (later) | **Building ‚Äî the rulebook check is in** | The checker now answers **two separate questions** about an AI-shopping menu answer: is it **correctly shaped** (does it follow the official published rulebook ‚Äî the real UCP data-format standard, 78 schema files fetched from the official source, pinned and tamper-locked), and is it **true** (does it match the restaurant's own records)? The headline demonstration landed with it: a menu answer that is **perfectly shaped by the official rulebook yet quotes a wrong price ‚Äî the shape check passes it, our truth check catches it**, proven by a test, not a story. That single exhibit IS the project's argument: format police aren't fact-checkers, and the fact-checker seat is the one this tool takes. Also today: the promised independent review of yesterday's inline build step ran (verdict: engineering solid; two narrow honesty gaps found and fixed the same morning ‚Äî the review working exactly as designed), and 35 machine-generated test documents now exercise the shape-checker, all reproducible from a seed. One honest limit, on the record: the *official* reference validator is written in a language (Rust) not installed on this machine, so "our checker agrees with the official one" is **built but not yet measured here** ‚Äî owner call to install the toolchain or measure elsewhere; no agreement is claimed meanwhile. |
